## 8. Authentication & Authorization

### Proxy-Based Auth

Production auth relies on a reverse proxy (OAuth proxy / OpenShift) that sets headers:

```
x-forwarded-email: user@redhat.com
x-forwarded-user: username
```

The `extractUser` middleware reads these headers, upserts the user in DB, and attaches `req.user`:

```typescript
app.use('/api/launches', extractUser, launchesRouter);
```

### Dev Mode

When `AUTH_ENABLED=false`:
- Uses a hardcoded `DEV_USER` (admin role)
- Supports `?impersonate=other@redhat.com` for testing other roles (development only)
- Logs a warning on first request

### Authorization Guards

```typescript
import { requireAdmin, requireOwnerOrAdmin, getSubscriptionOwner } from './middleware/auth';

router.delete('/:id', requireAdmin, handler);
router.put('/:id', requireOwnerOrAdmin(getSubscriptionOwner), handler);
```

- `requireAdmin`: returns 403 unless `req.user.role === 'admin'`
- `requireOwnerOrAdmin(getOwnerId)`: admin passes; others must own the resource

### Express Type Augmentation

`req.user` is typed via namespace augmentation in `auth.ts`:

```typescript
declare global {
  namespace Express {
    interface Request {
      user?: User;
    }
  }
}
```

